1
00:00:00,942 --> 00:00:30,830
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambodassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambodassam Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sama Sambodassam Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and fully Self-Enlightened One.

2
00:00:33,005 --> 00:01:02,100
So we're struggling our way through the Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta which is the turning of the wheel of the law and we call it the first discourse not that it was actually what he said but it just contains the platform of all his teachings and it's basically telling us that the middle path, the path is not one of indulging in the world nor in exercising these mortifications

3
00:01:03,531 --> 00:01:31,682
and then he goes on to explain these four noble truths the truth of suffering the origin of suffering the cessation of the path leading to the end of suffering and we're up to the second part there and this is how it reads from Bhikkhu Bodhi now this monks is the noble truth of the origin of suffering it is this craving that leads to renewed existence accompanied by delight and lust

4
00:01:32,236 --> 00:01:34,138
seeking delight here and there.

5
00:01:35,040 --> 00:01:44,334
That is, craving for sensual pleasures, craving for existence, craving for extermination.

6
00:01:44,353 --> 00:01:47,418
Now, I go through that again.

7
00:01:47,438 --> 00:01:52,085
Some of Bhikkhu Bodhi's translations are a bit heavy.

8
00:01:53,769 --> 00:01:58,155
I'll give you alternative translations which I think make a little bit more sense.

9
00:01:58,174 --> 00:02:01,180
Now, this, monks, is the noble truth for the arising

10
00:02:02,307 --> 00:02:32,009
of suffering in other words how does suffering arise origin for me is just a little bit too strong because the original cause is ignorance but how is it how do we experience the arising of suffering where does it begin and it is this craving so on dependent origination it's the word tanha which translates as thirst craving sense of lack

11
00:02:32,733 --> 00:03:02,486
and so this craving that leads to renewed existence we'll come to that in a minute accompanied by delight and lust you have to take that as meaning both the emotional pleasures we get out of life and the physical pleasures lust is a bit too confined a word really it's delighting in sensual pleasures seeking delight here and there

12
00:03:02,804 --> 00:03:28,861
so what the Buddha is suggesting is that our lives are constantly a movement towards what is pleasant trying to escape what is unpleasant and in finding something pleasant we form an attachment to it, we indulge it and remember there is an inbuilt obsolescence with pleasure

13
00:03:29,550 --> 00:03:56,419
you know what makes what made you what made you excited yesterday is now boring you can't you know you've got that your boiled sweet has to have a different flavor you just get boring so this this business of seeking pleasure here and there you see and it's desire which is the mechanism the first mechanism that comes so you can you can

14
00:03:56,804 --> 00:04:23,266
I mean the best place I think you can sort of see this is when you eat so having prepared yourself a meal just sit there for a moment and just catch your relationship to that meal a part of it will be just ordinary appetite and that's of course a desire but that's a good desire because it wants to nourish the body but the other desire is seeking happiness in sensual pleasure seeking delight

15
00:04:23,617 --> 00:04:26,680
in sensual pleasure.

16
00:04:27,721 --> 00:04:31,906
And that's indulgence.

17
00:04:31,925 --> 00:04:34,288
You have to be careful with this English word desire.

18
00:04:35,350 --> 00:04:36,651
Not all desires are bad.

19
00:04:36,730 --> 00:04:40,394
The desire to meditate is hardly something which is unwholesome.

20
00:04:40,435 --> 00:04:41,576
It leads to liberation.

21
00:04:42,237 --> 00:04:45,579
The Buddha himself desired to go on alms round to get some food.

22
00:04:46,901 --> 00:04:49,884
When people asked him a question he desired to answer it.

23
00:04:49,904 --> 00:04:51,607
So you've got to be careful with desire.

24
00:04:51,646 --> 00:04:53,067
It's a specific desire

25
00:04:53,538 --> 00:04:57,403
it's a wrong desire, it's a desire based on wrong understanding.

26
00:04:58,084 --> 00:04:58,764
Right?

27
00:04:58,785 --> 00:05:01,327
Which is seeking happiness in the sensual world.

28
00:05:02,009 --> 00:05:03,269
Right?

29
00:05:03,290 --> 00:05:08,557
So, he says this is the reason for the arising of suffering, is this desire.

30
00:05:09,317 --> 00:05:12,081
You can call it the psychological reason.

31
00:05:12,541 --> 00:05:13,862
The psychological reason.

32
00:05:15,485 --> 00:05:22,033
Actually speaking, if we're aware of desire, you see, we're not actually suffering.

33
00:05:22,334 --> 00:05:23,055
It's when we

34
00:05:24,149 --> 00:05:53,834
identify with the desire that the suffering is felt and that's on that dependent origination that's the grasping of it anyway that's perhaps a little too detailed for such a short talk but he points out that we've got to observe desires as they come and it's in knowing a desire to be unwholesome and in just waiting for it to pass away that we decondition that

35
00:05:54,202 --> 00:06:22,319
that desire within the heart and when we see a desire which is wholesome if we empower it then that's the conditioning which will grow in the heart so in the Eightfold Path you'll see we move from selfishness to generosity hatred to love, cruelty to compassion and it's done by recognizing a desire as unwholesome not reinforcing it, not acting on it

36
00:06:23,497 --> 00:06:51,615
when you see one that's good then you act upon it in this way you just change yourself very simple the mechanism is very simple but it's not easy of course now he says to renewed existence right now existence is every time a self arises it's a becoming a constant state of becoming of a making of an I so when you're asleep this isn't happening see

37
00:06:52,067 --> 00:06:53,850
As soon as you wake up, you say, oh, here I am.

38
00:06:54,370 --> 00:06:56,494
The eye has risen, right?

39
00:06:56,514 --> 00:06:59,497
And it says, got to get up and got to get some breakfast.

40
00:06:59,517 --> 00:07:07,810
And this eye is constantly recreating itself through its actions.

41
00:07:08,951 --> 00:07:19,206
Now that's what this, now he's translated it as existence, but actually the Pali word bhava is better translated by becoming, constant state of becoming.

42
00:07:19,742 --> 00:07:26,250
And if that state of becoming is driven by wrong understanding, that's what we mean by samsara.

43
00:07:26,730 --> 00:07:38,903
Samsara, the world of constantly onward going, onward going, the rotation, the day in and the day out, the moment in, the moment out, that's what we mean by samsara.

44
00:07:41,526 --> 00:07:44,550
So I think it's better translated by renewed becoming.

45
00:07:46,471 --> 00:07:49,716
So then he posits what these cravings are

46
00:07:49,966 --> 00:07:54,211
So the first one is the one we've discussed, which is the craving for sensual pleasure.

47
00:07:56,014 --> 00:08:06,428
Sensual pleasure, I mean, he's including here everything that, all the joys and happinesses that the world has to offer us.

48
00:08:07,750 --> 00:08:14,901
He's talking about sensual pleasure meaning all the joys and pleasures of life.

49
00:08:15,581 --> 00:08:19,247
It's the desire, it's the wrong desire for them

50
00:08:19,632 --> 00:08:20,552
which is the problem.

51
00:08:21,673 --> 00:08:31,603
The wrong desire manifests as an indulgence, it manifests as compulsive behavior, addiction, it manifests as frustration when you don't get it, and so on.

52
00:08:33,144 --> 00:08:35,548
So then you know that's a wrong desire.

53
00:08:37,208 --> 00:08:42,073
But then he says it's craving for, he translates existence, craving for becoming.

54
00:08:42,794 --> 00:08:45,658
So we're constantly trying to create the future.

55
00:08:46,217 --> 00:08:48,120
Constantly, that's the whole business of planning.

56
00:08:48,522 --> 00:08:53,489
what I'm going to do tomorrow, what I'm going to do next year, what I'm going to do when I'm retired, what I'm going to do when I'm dead.

57
00:08:53,990 --> 00:08:57,936
And he's constantly trying to work out the future, you see.

58
00:08:58,395 --> 00:09:02,783
So this desire to constantly become, become, become.

59
00:09:03,504 --> 00:09:09,692
And most of us do that because if we're not becoming, we must be dying.

60
00:09:12,677 --> 00:09:18,225
Now, then he also says, of course, craving for, here he translates it as extermination.

61
00:09:18,592 --> 00:09:22,619
but I slightly prefer the usual word, which is annihilation.

62
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:27,164
So that's, at worst, of course, that's suicide.

63
00:09:28,226 --> 00:09:36,458
So life gets so horrible, so unbearable, for one reason or another, that one wants to get rid of the self, and that's suicide.

64
00:09:36,479 --> 00:09:39,102
But we also do it in little bits and bobs, you see.

65
00:09:39,503 --> 00:09:47,014
When we're a bit bored, a bit depressed, you think, oh, to hell with it, and you launch yourself onto the sofa or couch and just fall asleep.

66
00:09:47,585 --> 00:09:49,527
So you block out for a while.

67
00:09:49,947 --> 00:09:52,070
Every time you do that, you're self-annihilating.

68
00:09:54,092 --> 00:10:02,783
And that's one of the causes why we feel in meditation, but also in daily life, the dullness and the lethargy sometimes comes up.

69
00:10:02,802 --> 00:10:06,648
And that's because we've pushed all this stuff down through sleep.

70
00:10:06,727 --> 00:10:07,950
Sleep's a great suppressant.

71
00:10:08,791 --> 00:10:11,192
And often you wake up and you are feeling better.

72
00:10:11,653 --> 00:10:15,538
But actually you've pushed stuff away, you see.

73
00:10:15,558 --> 00:10:16,679
So that's what...

74
00:10:17,115 --> 00:10:22,964
this idea of seeking, craving for non-existence, you see.

75
00:10:23,524 --> 00:10:27,009
Craving, that's better actually, craving for not becoming.

76
00:10:27,331 --> 00:10:33,460
Although you have to be careful here because the enlightened person is no longer in that state of creating this self.

77
00:10:34,802 --> 00:10:37,706
So remember, when the Buddha was enlightened, he didn't sort of disappear.

78
00:10:38,667 --> 00:10:41,471
He kept being a human being.

79
00:10:42,613 --> 00:10:44,034
But he didn't suffer from this, you see.

80
00:10:44,250 --> 00:11:13,886
so this creating of a becoming is to do with a self and the self isn't an object, it's not a thing, it's a process so the self is always changing depending on what it happens to be doing at the time so if you were to define yourself you might define yourself variously as a friend, by your profession

81
00:11:14,238 --> 00:11:42,472
as a mother, a father, you know, like, the definition of self keeps changing, see, a sociological self, an existential self, I've got a list of selves somewhere that somebody wrote, there's about 30 of them, but I mean, that can't be exhaustive, because every time there's a self, there's a type, so it's selfing, that would be a better word, it's constant selfing, and

82
00:11:43,870 --> 00:11:54,083
that arises out of a wrong relationship with the world, with the body, with the heart and mind, where you're saying, this is me.

83
00:11:55,625 --> 00:12:06,601
So the liberation is when that sense of this is me disappears, but there is still that awareness.

84
00:12:07,602 --> 00:12:11,227
The Buddha is awareness within the world, but not of it.

85
00:12:12,304 --> 00:12:13,947
That relationship has been broken.

86
00:12:14,488 --> 00:12:18,932
Therefore, it's impossible for that person to suffer.

87
00:12:20,495 --> 00:12:36,836
Now, in your meditation, when you become the objective observer within yourself, and you're observing maybe some physical pain or something, or you're observing an emotion, you're feeling it, feeling an emotion, you see an image, all these things have been objectified.

88
00:12:37,176 --> 00:12:38,498
They're an object to you.

89
00:12:38,917 --> 00:12:43,501
So whatever knows has extracted itself out of this body, heart and mind.

90
00:12:44,163 --> 00:12:44,342
See?

91
00:12:44,903 --> 00:12:48,147
And when you're in that position and you come out of it, just reflect a bit.

92
00:12:48,407 --> 00:12:49,508
What was it like being there?

93
00:12:51,890 --> 00:12:55,674
It's very different from being a physical self like when you trap your finger in a door.

94
00:12:56,155 --> 00:12:57,977
See, for that one moment you are the finger.

95
00:12:58,597 --> 00:12:59,399
Huh?

96
00:12:59,418 --> 00:13:00,379
As a physical self.

97
00:13:00,639 --> 00:13:06,346
It's very different from being an emotional self when you lose it and you just find yourself swallowing about or getting angry.

98
00:13:06,667 --> 00:13:06,746
Huh?

99
00:13:07,164 --> 00:13:10,009
They're different from a thinking self when you're just lost in thought.

100
00:13:12,312 --> 00:13:13,375
It's another position, isn't it?

101
00:13:13,875 --> 00:13:14,657
Something else, right?

102
00:13:15,438 --> 00:13:22,149
There's no thought, there's no emotions, and there's no body when you're the observer, when you're the feeler, is it?

103
00:13:23,652 --> 00:13:26,777
Now, if you haven't experienced that, then you have to come here and do a week's retreat.

104
00:13:37,456 --> 00:13:50,496
Because that's what the Buddha says, when you are mindful, and he's talking about this sort of level of mindfulness, you are in the presence of Nibbāna, as he's worked, in the presence of Nibbāna, you're in the vicinity of Nibbāna.

105
00:13:50,517 --> 00:13:51,719
So we're very close to it.

106
00:13:54,003 --> 00:14:04,779
So that's basically how he phrases the noble truth of the arising of suffering, for the arising of suffering, or the origin of suffering.

107
00:14:05,434 --> 00:14:15,009
It is this craving this craving that we have that leads to renewed becoming accompanied by delight and lust seeking delight here and there.

108
00:14:15,571 --> 00:14:27,409
That is craving for sensual pleasures craving for becoming and craving for annihilation.

109
00:14:27,429 --> 00:14:31,375
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

110
00:14:31,395 --> 00:14:32,758
May you by your

111
00:14:33,126 --> 00:14:45,465
clear understanding of desire, liberate yourself from all suffering sooner rather than later.

